1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:03,925
One additional option that we have for plotting one quantitative variable

2
00:00:03,925 --> 00:00:08,440
against one qualitative variable is the adaptation of bar charts.

3
00:00:08,440 --> 00:00:10,910
Instead of showing counts on the vertical axis,

4
00:00:10,910 --> 00:00:13,240
we can show the mean of a second variable.

5
00:00:13,240 --> 00:00:15,030
To do this, we need to make use of

6
00:00:15,030 --> 00:00:18,245
a different function than the count plot function that we had before.

7
00:00:18,245 --> 00:00:22,125
Instead, Seaborn's bar plot function will be what we want.

8
00:00:22,125 --> 00:00:24,670
I'll add a label to the y-axis so that it's

9
00:00:24,670 --> 00:00:27,620
clear that we're plotting the means on the y-axis.

10
00:00:27,620 --> 00:00:29,440
Since we have a bar plot,

11
00:00:29,440 --> 00:00:32,760
the bottom limit of the y-axis has been set to zero.

12
00:00:32,760 --> 00:00:37,425
The black lines on each bar indicate uncertainty about the mean as a confidence info.

13
00:00:37,425 --> 00:00:39,615
Since we have a lot of data available,

14
00:00:39,615 --> 00:00:42,030
the uncertainty whiskers are quite small.

15
00:00:42,030 --> 00:00:44,545
If we want to leave these whiskers out of the plot,

16
00:00:44,545 --> 00:00:47,900
we can do so by setting air width equals zero.

17
00:00:47,900 --> 00:00:51,740
Alternatively, we could change the bars to represent the standard deviation of

18
00:00:51,740 --> 00:00:55,995
data points by setting the parameter ci equals sd.

19
00:00:55,995 --> 00:00:58,920
If having the zero lower bound isn't of interest,

20
00:00:58,920 --> 00:01:02,950
then you can choose the point plot function instead of the bar plot function.

21
00:01:02,950 --> 00:01:05,360
We actually don't need to set the base color in

22
00:01:05,360 --> 00:01:08,610
this case for everything to show up as the same color.

23
00:01:08,610 --> 00:01:10,215
Note that by default,

24
00:01:10,215 --> 00:01:12,575
the points are connected by a line.

25
00:01:12,575 --> 00:01:17,810
This isn't a problem in this case since vehicle classes ordered from smallest to largest.

26
00:01:17,810 --> 00:01:20,675
But if we were plotting a nominal variable instead,

27
00:01:20,675 --> 00:01:25,600
we could turn off the line by setting line styles to an empty string.

